1
00:00:12,095 --> 00:00:13,935
In the last video, along with the ideas

2
00:00:13,935 --> 00:00:16,175
of vector addition and scalar multiplication,

3
00:00:16,175 --> 00:00:18,095
I described vector coordinates,

4
00:00:18,095 --> 00:00:20,095
where there's this back and forth between, for

5
00:00:20,095 --> 00:00:23,135
example, pairs of numbers and two dimensional vectors.

6
00:00:23,695 --> 00:00:26,015
Now, I imagine the vector coordinates were already

7
00:00:26,015 --> 00:00:27,880
familiar to a lot of you, but there's

8
00:00:27,880 --> 00:00:29,640
another kind of interesting way to think about

9
00:00:29,640 --> 00:00:31,720
these coordinates, which is pretty central to linear

10
00:00:31,720 --> 00:00:32,440
algebra.

11
00:00:32,760 --> 00:00:34,280
When you have a pair of numbers that's

12
00:00:34,280 --> 00:00:36,680
meant to describe a vector, like three, negative

13
00:00:36,680 --> 00:00:38,920
two, I want you to think about each

14
00:00:38,920 --> 00:00:42,035
coordinate as a scalar, meaning think about how

15
00:00:42,035 --> 00:00:44,595
each one stretches or squishes vectors.

16
00:00:45,075 --> 00:00:47,235
In the x y coordinate system, there are

17
00:00:47,235 --> 00:00:48,835
two very special vectors.

18
00:00:48,915 --> 00:00:50,595
The one pointing to the right with length

19
00:00:50,595 --> 00:00:53,475
one, commonly called I hat or the unit

20
00:00:53,475 --> 00:00:55,630
vector in the x direction, and the one

21
00:00:55,630 --> 00:00:58,350
pointing straight up with length one, commonly called

22
00:00:58,350 --> 00:01:00,590
j hat or the unit vector in the

23
00:01:00,590 --> 00:01:01,470
y direction.

24
00:01:02,270 --> 00:01:04,190
Now think of the x coordinate of our

25
00:01:04,190 --> 00:01:06,990
vector as a scalar that scales I hat,

26
00:01:06,990 --> 00:01:09,095
stretching it by a factor of three, and

27
00:01:09,095 --> 00:01:11,255
the y coordinate as a scalar that scales

28
00:01:11,255 --> 00:01:13,495
j hat, flipping it and stretching it by

29
00:01:13,495 --> 00:01:14,535
a factor of two.

30
00:01:14,855 --> 00:01:17,335
In this sense, the vector that these coordinates

31
00:01:17,335 --> 00:01:20,295
describe is the sum of two scaled vectors.

32
00:01:20,880 --> 00:01:23,520
That's a surprisingly important concept, this idea of

33
00:01:23,520 --> 00:01:25,840
adding together two scaled vectors.

34
00:01:27,200 --> 00:01:29,200
Those two vectors, I hat and j hat,

35
00:01:29,200 --> 00:01:31,440
have a special name by the way. Together,

36
00:01:31,440 --> 00:01:33,600
they're called the basis of a coordinate system.

37
00:01:34,105 --> 00:01:36,345
What this means basically is that when you

38
00:01:36,345 --> 00:01:38,985
think about coordinates as scalars, the basis vectors

39
00:01:38,985 --> 00:01:42,025
are what those scalars actually, you know, scale.

40
00:01:42,345 --> 00:01:44,905
There's also a more technical definition, but I'll

41
00:01:44,905 --> 00:01:45,625
get to that later.

42
00:01:47,480 --> 00:01:49,640
By framing our coordinate system in terms of

43
00:01:49,640 --> 00:01:51,640
these two special basis vectors,

44
00:01:51,720 --> 00:01:54,200
it raises a pretty interesting and subtle point.

45
00:01:54,440 --> 00:01:57,160
We could have chosen different basis vectors and

46
00:01:57,160 --> 00:02:00,520
gotten a completely reasonable new coordinate system.

47
00:02:01,025 --> 00:02:03,425
For example, take some vector pointing up and

48
00:02:03,425 --> 00:02:05,265
to the right along with some other vector

49
00:02:05,265 --> 00:02:06,785
pointing down and to the right in some

50
00:02:06,785 --> 00:02:09,025
way. Take a moment to think about all

51
00:02:09,025 --> 00:02:11,025
the different vectors that you can get by

52
00:02:11,025 --> 00:02:12,625
choosing two scalars,

53
00:02:13,025 --> 00:02:14,785
using each one to scale one of the

54
00:02:14,785 --> 00:02:17,370
vectors, then adding together what you get.

55
00:02:17,770 --> 00:02:19,850
Which two dimensional vectors can you reach by

56
00:02:19,850 --> 00:02:21,850
altering the choices of scalars?

57
00:02:24,570 --> 00:02:26,570
The answer is that you can reach every

58
00:02:26,570 --> 00:02:29,050
possible two dimensional vector and I think it's

59
00:02:29,050 --> 00:02:30,570
a good puzzle to contemplate why.

60
00:02:32,255 --> 00:02:34,415
A new pair of basis vectors like this

61
00:02:34,415 --> 00:02:36,175
still gives us a valid way to go

62
00:02:36,175 --> 00:02:38,255
back and forth between pairs of numbers and

63
00:02:38,255 --> 00:02:39,615
two dimensional vectors,

64
00:02:39,855 --> 00:02:42,335
but the association is definitely different from the

65
00:02:42,335 --> 00:02:44,175
one that you get using the more standard

66
00:02:44,175 --> 00:02:46,730
basis of I hat and j hat. This

67
00:02:46,730 --> 00:02:48,410
is something I'll go into much more detail

68
00:02:48,410 --> 00:02:51,690
on later, describing the exact relationship between different

69
00:02:51,690 --> 00:02:52,810
coordinate systems.

70
00:02:52,890 --> 00:02:54,170
But for right now, I just want you

71
00:02:54,170 --> 00:02:56,650
to appreciate the fact that anytime we describe

72
00:02:56,650 --> 00:02:57,930
vectors numerically,

73
00:02:58,010 --> 00:03:00,090
it depends on an implicit choice of what

74
00:03:00,090 --> 00:03:01,290
basis vectors we're using.

75
00:03:02,345 --> 00:03:04,665
So anytime that you're scaling two vectors and

76
00:03:04,665 --> 00:03:06,825
adding them like this, it's called a linear

77
00:03:06,825 --> 00:03:07,625
combination

78
00:03:07,625 --> 00:03:09,065
of those two vectors.

79
00:03:11,225 --> 00:03:12,985
Where does this word linear come from? Why

80
00:03:12,985 --> 00:03:14,425
does this have anything to do with lines?

81
00:03:14,770 --> 00:03:16,930
Well, this isn't the etymology, but one way

82
00:03:16,930 --> 00:03:18,370
I like to think about it is that

83
00:03:18,370 --> 00:03:20,210
if you fix one of those scalars and

84
00:03:20,210 --> 00:03:22,290
let the other one change its value freely,

85
00:03:22,450 --> 00:03:25,010
the tip of the resulting vector draws a

86
00:03:25,010 --> 00:03:25,570
straight line.

87
00:03:29,025 --> 00:03:31,345
Now, if you let both scalars range freely

88
00:03:31,345 --> 00:03:33,745
and consider every possible vector that you can

89
00:03:33,745 --> 00:03:35,825
get, there are two things that can happen.

90
00:03:36,385 --> 00:03:38,225
For most pairs of vectors, you'll be able

91
00:03:38,225 --> 00:03:40,145
to reach every possible point in the plane.

92
00:03:40,510 --> 00:03:43,230
Every two dimensional vector is within your grasp.

93
00:03:43,470 --> 00:03:45,390
However, in the unlucky case where your two

94
00:03:45,390 --> 00:03:48,030
original vectors happen to line up, the tip

95
00:03:48,030 --> 00:03:50,350
of the resulting vector is limited to just

96
00:03:50,350 --> 00:03:52,350
this single line passing through the origin.

97
00:03:53,895 --> 00:03:56,615
Actually, technically there's a third possibility too. Both

98
00:03:56,615 --> 00:03:58,535
your vectors could be zero, in which case

99
00:03:58,535 --> 00:04:00,535
you'd just be stuck at the origin.

100
00:04:01,255 --> 00:04:02,775
Here's some more terminology.

101
00:04:02,935 --> 00:04:04,935
The set of all possible vectors that you

102
00:04:04,935 --> 00:04:07,095
can reach with a linear combination of a

103
00:04:07,095 --> 00:04:09,630
given pair of vectors is called the span

104
00:04:09,630 --> 00:04:11,150
of those two vectors.

105
00:04:14,430 --> 00:04:16,350
So restating what we just saw in this

106
00:04:16,350 --> 00:04:18,510
lingo, the span of most pairs of two

107
00:04:18,510 --> 00:04:20,510
d vectors is all vectors of two d

108
00:04:20,510 --> 00:04:22,830
space. But when they line up, their span

109
00:04:22,830 --> 00:04:25,255
is all vectors whose tip sit on a

110
00:04:25,255 --> 00:04:26,055
certain line.

111
00:04:27,015 --> 00:04:29,495
Remember how I said that linear algebra revolves

112
00:04:29,495 --> 00:04:31,815
around vector addition and scalar multiplication?

113
00:04:32,215 --> 00:04:34,695
Well, the span of two vectors is basically

114
00:04:34,695 --> 00:04:36,535
a way of asking what are all the

115
00:04:36,535 --> 00:04:39,015
possible vectors you can reach using only these

116
00:04:39,015 --> 00:04:40,375
two fundamental operations,

117
00:04:40,670 --> 00:04:42,750
vector addition and scalar multiplication.

118
00:04:43,470 --> 00:04:44,750
This is a good time to talk about

119
00:04:44,750 --> 00:04:47,550
how people commonly think about vectors as points.

120
00:04:47,870 --> 00:04:49,710
It gets really crowded to think about a

121
00:04:49,710 --> 00:04:52,110
whole collection of vectors sitting on a line

122
00:04:52,110 --> 00:04:53,870
and more crowded still to think about all

123
00:04:53,870 --> 00:04:56,135
two dimensional vectors all at once filling up

124
00:04:56,135 --> 00:04:56,855
the plane.

125
00:04:57,175 --> 00:04:59,495
So, when dealing with collections of vectors like

126
00:04:59,495 --> 00:05:01,975
this, it's common to represent each one with

127
00:05:01,975 --> 00:05:03,575
just a point in space.

128
00:05:03,815 --> 00:05:05,495
The point at the tip of that vector

129
00:05:05,495 --> 00:05:07,655
where, as usual, I want you thinking about

130
00:05:07,655 --> 00:05:09,655
that vector with its tail on the origin.

131
00:05:10,580 --> 00:05:12,420
That way, if you want to think about

132
00:05:12,420 --> 00:05:14,660
every possible vector whose tip sits on a

133
00:05:14,660 --> 00:05:17,540
certain line, just think about the line itself.

134
00:05:20,020 --> 00:05:22,660
Likewise, to think about all possible two dimensional

135
00:05:22,660 --> 00:05:24,895
vectors all at once, conceptualize

136
00:05:24,895 --> 00:05:27,055
each one as the point where its tip

137
00:05:27,055 --> 00:05:29,615
sits. So, effect, what you'll be thinking about

138
00:05:29,615 --> 00:05:32,015
is the infinite flat sheet of two dimensional

139
00:05:32,015 --> 00:05:34,255
space itself, leaving the arrows out of it.

140
00:05:36,110 --> 00:05:38,030
In general, if you're thinking about a vector

141
00:05:38,030 --> 00:05:39,550
on its own, think of it as an

142
00:05:39,550 --> 00:05:40,190
arrow.

143
00:05:40,430 --> 00:05:41,950
And if you're dealing with a collection of

144
00:05:41,950 --> 00:05:43,870
vectors, it's convenient to think of them all

145
00:05:43,870 --> 00:05:44,750
as points.

146
00:05:45,230 --> 00:05:47,470
So, for our span example, the span of

147
00:05:47,470 --> 00:05:49,645
most pairs of vectors ends up being the

148
00:05:49,645 --> 00:05:52,205
entire infinite sheet of two dimensional space.

149
00:05:52,285 --> 00:05:54,205
But, if they line up, their span is

150
00:05:54,205 --> 00:05:55,245
just a line.

151
00:05:58,445 --> 00:05:59,965
The idea of span gets a lot more

152
00:05:59,965 --> 00:06:02,205
interesting if we start thinking about vectors in

153
00:06:02,205 --> 00:06:03,005
three-dimensional

154
00:06:03,005 --> 00:06:03,245
space.

155
00:06:03,920 --> 00:06:06,240
For example, if you take two vectors in

156
00:06:06,240 --> 00:06:08,080
three d space that are not pointing in

157
00:06:08,080 --> 00:06:08,960
the same direction,

158
00:06:09,280 --> 00:06:11,120
what does it mean to take their span?

159
00:06:13,280 --> 00:06:15,680
Well, their span is the collection of all

160
00:06:15,680 --> 00:06:17,520
possible linear combinations

161
00:06:17,520 --> 00:06:19,675
of those two vectors. Meaning,

162
00:06:19,835 --> 00:06:22,395
all possible vectors you get by scaling each

163
00:06:22,395 --> 00:06:23,755
of the two of them in some way

164
00:06:23,755 --> 00:06:25,275
and then adding them together.

165
00:06:25,915 --> 00:06:27,995
You can kind of imagine turning two different

166
00:06:27,995 --> 00:06:30,715
knobs to change the two scalars defining the

167
00:06:30,715 --> 00:06:33,620
linear combination, adding the scaled vectors and following

168
00:06:33,620 --> 00:06:35,460
the tip of the resulting vector.

169
00:06:36,020 --> 00:06:37,940
That tip will trace out some kind of

170
00:06:37,940 --> 00:06:40,740
flat sheet cutting through the origin of three-dimensional

171
00:06:40,740 --> 00:06:41,380
space.

172
00:06:41,860 --> 00:06:43,940
This flat sheet is the span of the

173
00:06:43,940 --> 00:06:44,580
two vectors,

174
00:06:45,055 --> 00:06:47,455
or more precisely, the set of all possible

175
00:06:47,455 --> 00:06:49,695
vectors whose tips sit on that flat sheet

176
00:06:49,695 --> 00:06:51,535
is the span of your two vectors.

177
00:06:51,775 --> 00:06:53,695
Isn't that a beautiful mental image?

178
00:06:54,735 --> 00:06:56,575
So, what happens if we add a third

179
00:06:56,575 --> 00:06:58,735
vector and consider the span of all three

180
00:06:58,735 --> 00:06:59,295
of those guys?

181
00:07:00,580 --> 00:07:03,140
A linear combination of three vectors is defined

182
00:07:03,140 --> 00:07:04,660
pretty much the same way as it is

183
00:07:04,660 --> 00:07:07,220
for two. You'll choose three different scalars,

184
00:07:07,300 --> 00:07:09,620
scale each of those vectors, and then add

185
00:07:09,620 --> 00:07:10,340
them all together.

186
00:07:16,275 --> 00:07:18,675
And again, the span of these vectors is

187
00:07:18,675 --> 00:07:20,915
the set of all possible linear combinations.

188
00:07:24,530 --> 00:07:26,690
Two different things could happen here. If your

189
00:07:26,690 --> 00:07:28,930
third vector happens to be sitting on the

190
00:07:28,930 --> 00:07:30,290
span of the first two,

191
00:07:30,530 --> 00:07:32,290
then the span doesn't change. You're sort of

192
00:07:32,290 --> 00:07:34,850
trapped on that same flat sheet. In other

193
00:07:34,850 --> 00:07:36,930
words, adding a scaled version of that third

194
00:07:36,930 --> 00:07:38,850
vector to the linear combination

195
00:07:38,845 --> 00:07:40,765
doesn't really give you access to any new

196
00:07:40,765 --> 00:07:41,485
vectors.

197
00:07:42,685 --> 00:07:44,445
But if you just randomly choose a third

198
00:07:44,445 --> 00:07:47,005
vector, it's almost certainly not sitting on the

199
00:07:47,005 --> 00:07:48,365
span of those first two.

200
00:07:48,765 --> 00:07:51,005
Then, since it's pointing in a separate direction,

201
00:07:51,165 --> 00:07:54,365
it unlocks access to every possible three-dimensional vector.

202
00:07:55,400 --> 00:07:56,920
One way I like to think about this

203
00:07:56,920 --> 00:07:59,000
is that as you scale that new third

204
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:02,120
vector, it moves around that span sheet of

205
00:08:02,120 --> 00:08:04,200
the first two, sweeping it through all of

206
00:08:04,200 --> 00:08:04,760
space.

207
00:08:05,800 --> 00:08:07,240
Another way to think about it is that

208
00:08:07,240 --> 00:08:09,480
you're making full use of the three freely

209
00:08:09,480 --> 00:08:11,935
changing scalars you have at your disposal to

210
00:08:11,935 --> 00:08:14,415
access the full three dimensions of space.

211
00:08:16,895 --> 00:08:18,815
Now, in the case where the third vector

212
00:08:18,815 --> 00:08:20,655
was already sitting on the span of the

213
00:08:20,655 --> 00:08:22,495
first two, or the case where two vectors

214
00:08:22,495 --> 00:08:24,660
happen to line up, we want some terminology

215
00:08:24,660 --> 00:08:26,420
to describe the fact that at least one

216
00:08:26,420 --> 00:08:29,060
of these vectors is redundant, not adding anything

217
00:08:29,060 --> 00:08:30,020
to our span.

218
00:08:30,740 --> 00:08:33,140
Whenever this happens, where you have multiple vectors

219
00:08:33,140 --> 00:08:35,060
and you could remove one without reducing the

220
00:08:35,060 --> 00:08:37,895
span, the relevant terminology is to say that

221
00:08:37,895 --> 00:08:39,815
they are linearly dependent.

222
00:08:40,295 --> 00:08:42,135
Another way of phrasing that would be to

223
00:08:42,135 --> 00:08:43,895
say that one of the vectors can be

224
00:08:43,895 --> 00:08:46,295
expressed as a linear combination of the others

225
00:08:46,295 --> 00:08:48,295
since it's already in the span of the

226
00:08:48,295 --> 00:08:48,615
others.

227
00:08:52,850 --> 00:08:55,090
On the other hand, if each vector really

228
00:08:55,090 --> 00:08:57,650
does add another dimension to the span, they're

229
00:08:57,650 --> 00:08:59,650
said to be linearly independent.

230
00:09:06,305 --> 00:09:08,465
So, with all of that terminology, and hopefully

231
00:09:08,465 --> 00:09:10,065
with some good mental images to go with

232
00:09:10,065 --> 00:09:11,585
it, let me leave you with a puzzle

233
00:09:11,585 --> 00:09:14,385
before we go. The technical definition of a

234
00:09:14,385 --> 00:09:16,770
basis of a space is a set of

235
00:09:16,770 --> 00:09:20,450
linearly independent vectors that span that space.

236
00:09:21,890 --> 00:09:24,370
Now, given how I described a basis earlier,

237
00:09:24,770 --> 00:09:26,610
and given your current understanding of the words

238
00:09:26,610 --> 00:09:28,450
span and linearly independent,

239
00:09:29,015 --> 00:09:31,975
think about why this definition would make sense.

240
00:09:33,975 --> 00:09:36,135
In the next video, I'll get into matrices

241
00:09:36,135 --> 00:09:38,135
in transforming space. See you then.
